[~sjones] what if we stop the Queue before removing from the workers.
        workers.get(worker.key()).stop();
        workers.remove(worker.key());
All workers then eventually return and the next call to ThreadPool.limitTo will shutdown the old executor service. 

Do you still see a potential issue with this?

[~spark], yes, at the moment there could be a thread in this code:

{code}
    if ( workers.containsKey( worker.key( ) ) ) {
      return ( Queue<T> ) workers.get( worker.key( ) );
    } ...
{code}

after the "containsKey", but before the "get" where a removal of a worker by another thread would lead to a null return. In this case you could skip the contains check and simply get the worker, returning only if not null.

{code}
    Queue<T> worker = ( Queue<T> ) workers.get( worker.key( ) );
    if ( worker != null ) {
      return worker;
    } ...
{code}

I think there is also a thread safety issue when adding/starting workers, that looks like it could result in a Queue being added to workers after it failed to start (in the case that another worker started successfully but had not yet been added to workers). In this case "putIfAbsent" could be used to determine the correct return Queue:

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3752194/best-practice-to-use-concurrentmaps-putifabsent

For thread safe removal/stop, I think you'd need something like:

{code}
      final Queue<T> removed = (Queue<T>) workers.remove( worker.key( ) );
      if ( removed != null ) {
        removed.stop( ) ;
      }
{code}

As you say, the next "limitTo" should then clean things up.
